The prostate is an organ in the male reproductive system that helps to produce the fluid that feeds and transports sperm. Many men are suffering from prostate-related issues these days, and ageing is thought to be a prevalent factor that raises the likelihood of having this condition. According to Webmd, two-thirds of all prostate cancers are diagnosed in males over the age of 65. As a result, it is vital to consume prostate-friendly meals, as they aid in the maintenance of a healthy prostate.
Certain foods, such as dairy, processed meat, alcohol, saturated fats, and others, should be avoided by those who have been diagnosed with prostate difficulties.
The 5 foods listed below are highly beneficial to prostrate health.
1. BroccoliGreen vegetables are an excellent idea if you want to avoid illness, but some are especially beneficial to maintaining a healthy prostate.
Sulforaphane is a cancer-fighting chemical found in vegetables like broccoli, kale, cabbage, and sprouts. A group of scientists from Texas A&M University’s Health Science Center discovered in 2015 that supplements containing the molecule could be used to treat advanced prostate cancer.
2. Tomatoes

Tomatoes have long been known to be beneficial to prostate health, with numerous studies from throughout the world confirming their usefulness in slowing the rapid growth of the prostate in later life.
It’s all because tomatoes are high in the vitamin lycopene, which is also responsible for their colour.
3. Coffee and Green Tea
A cup of coffee or tea in the morning can help you keep a healthy prostate. It’s not the caffeine, but some of the other active compounds in coffee that make a difference. Even if you prefer decaf coffee, it is still helpful. If you don’t care for coffee, try a cup of green tea instead.
4. Leafy greens
Cooked greens including spinach, mustard greens, and collard greens have been shown to reduce the risk of prostate cancer in studies.
5. Fatty fish
“Good fats” are found in some fish. These healthy fats do not induce inflammation like saturated animal fats do. Salmon, sardines, and trout are among the cold-water fish that contain them.
Scientists believe that inflammation in the prostate is a risk factor for cancer. Inflammation can make cancer more likely to spread.


